05169nam a22007215i 9780748633760DE-B159720220306030904.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220306t20222008stk    fo  d z      eng d  a97807486337607 a10.1515/97807486337602doi  a(DE-B1597)616608  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  astkcGB-SCT 4aNA1487.I8bB33 2018eb 7aARC0160002bisacsh04a720.955952231 aBabaie, Sussan, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aIsfahan and its Palaces :bStatecraft, Shi`ism and the Architecture of Conviviality in Early Modern Iran /cSussan Babaie. 1aEdinburgh : bEdinburgh University Press, c[2022] 4c©2008  a1 online resource (320 p.) :b60 B/W illustrations 24 colour illustrations 24 colour and 60 b+w illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aEdinburgh Studies in Islamic Art : ESIA00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Figures -- tList of Plates -- tSeries Editor’s Foreword -- tPreface and Acknowledgments -- tNote on the Transliteration System -- tSafavid Dynastic Chart -- tTimeline of Safavid Capital Cities and Major Structures -- tCHAPTER 1 Introduction: Conviviality, Charismatic Absolutism, and the Persianization of Shi'ism -- tCHAPTER 2 Peripatetic Kings and Palaces: From Tabriz to Qazvin in the Sixteenth Century -- tCHAPTER 3 Dwelling in Paradise, or Isfahan “Half the World” -- tCHAPTER 4 “The Abode of Felicitous Rule” or the Daulatkhane Royal Precinct -- tCHAPTER 5 The Spatial Choreography of Conviviality: the Palaces of Isfahan -- tCHAPTER 6 Feasting and the Perso-Shi'i Etiquette of Kingship -- tCHAPTER 7 Epilogue: The Fall of Isfahan -- tSelect Bibliography -- tIllustration Acknowledgments -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWinner of the Houshang Pourshariati Iranian Studies Book Award 2009This beautifully illustrated history of Safavid Isfahan (1501–1722) explores the architectural and urban forms and networks of socio-cultural action that reflected a distinctly early-modern and Perso-Shi‘i practice of kingship.An immense building campaign, initiated in 1590-91, transformed Isfahan from a provincial, medieval, and largely Sunni city into an urban-centered representation of the first Imami Shi‘i empire in the history of Islam. The historical process of Shi‘ification of Safavid Iran and the deployment of the arts in situating the shifts in the politico-religious agenda of the imperial household informs Sussan Babaie’s study of palatial architecture and urban environments of Isfahan and the earlier capitals of Tabriz and Qazvin.Babaie argues that since the Safavid claim presumed the inheritance both of the charisma of the Shi‘i Imams and of the aura of royal splendor integral to ancient Persian notions of kingship, a ceremonial regime was gradually devised in which access and proximity to the shah assumed the contours of an institutionalized form of feasting. Talar-palaces, a new typology in Islamic palatial designs, and the urban-spatial articulation of access and proximity are the architectural anchors of this argument. Cast in the comparative light of urban spaces and palace complexes elsewhere and earlier—in the Timurid, Ottoman, and Mughal realms as well as in the early modern European capitals—Safavid Isfahan emerges as the epitome of a new architectural-urban paradigm in the early modern age.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2022) 0aArchitecture, SafavidzIranzIṣfahān. 0aShiiteszIranzIṣfahān. 4aIslamic Studies. 7aARCHITECTURE / Buildings / Religious.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEdinburgh University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2013-2000z978311078046840uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978074863376040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780748633760423Coveruhttps